snippet.textDisplay:
This valentines day that was also my mom's birthday, the guy I was dating with (over a month) told me he met someome else, by message, doesn't even mention the word "breakup" he just said "I'm sorry" and expected me to end things, obiously I did, and cried a little bit while watching rom-coms, but after that I went to my mom's to sing her happy birthday and enjoy her company. The next day I was already feeling better, I didn't realize he was causing me such stress until I erased him from my life. I'm a helpless romantic, but now I romanticize the idea of my future and how great it can be. Being in love with myself makes it difficult for me to fall easily for somebody else.
Besides, all these dramas are great stories for when I'm older and have someone to listen to them.

snippet.textDisplay: I've been single for the last 3 years and like dating on and off for the last two. And I'm actually really happy when I'm single, and most of the time it's not really a boyfriend I am "looking for". Its more like a partner, best friend thing. Cause I've always had like a very close best friend, but now at 25 it's just not the same. I have like a circle of very close friends, but not like that one person I could call in the middle of the night or hang out with all the time. And I've always thought that I would be fine without a guy, I'm great with being alone and I have my friends and family. But honestly, I feel like most of my friends have partners and now it's like they're their "person". If they have free time they wanna spend it with their significant other. Especially feel this way since two of my closest friends started dating each other. So really, I am fine being single... I just want someone on my team, someone I can prioritize and who prioritizes me. Right now that person is me, which is fine too.

snippet.textDisplay: I've really wanted to write a non-traditional coming of age story for a long time. When I was a teenage(and beyond) I was soooooo hard on myself for missing all of the traditional milestones. I've still to this day never had a boyfriend, I had my first kiss when I was 18 and it wasn't even terribly romantic. Plus, I got in a really bad car wreck the day after my 16th birthday, which ruined all of my excitement for learning how to drive. Coming of age stories were my favorite genre as a young teen, so missing all of the important milestones was really devastating. I'd like to write a book or movie where growing up is more internal and/or friendship based, but it is so hard because of our expectations for adolescence and that kind of narrative
